# Unix / Linux / macOS crontab recipe for the daily kickoff.
#
# Install with:  crontab -e   (then paste an edited copy of the line below)
# List with:     crontab -l
#
# Requirements (see ../README.md):
#   - CONTENT_HOME must be set for the command (cron does NOT load your shell profile,
#     so set it inline on the line — that is what the leading assignment does).
#   - Replace <CONTENT_HOME>, <NODE_BIN>, <ENGINE_DIR>, and the HH:MM time.
#
# Fields:  minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week  command
# Example below runs every day at 08:30 host-local time.

30 8 * * *  CONTENT_HOME=<CONTENT_HOME> <NODE_BIN> <ENGINE_DIR>/bin/engine.js kickoff >> <CONTENT_HOME>/logs/kickoff.cron.log 2>&1

# OPTIONAL — the config-gated trend pass (release-spec section 8.8; OFF by default).
# Enable trends.enabled + trends.adapter + trends.cadence in config/system.json, reserve
# slot_type:trend calendar slots, then schedule poll-trends on the SAME interval as your
# cadence (1h/2h hourly, 24h daily). For the apify adapter, add the operator-confirmed
# trends.tracked_accounts + trends.keywords (suggest them free: engine suggest prompt
# tracked_accounts / keywords). The daily work-recap option needs NO extra line — the
# kickoff above fills it when work_recap.enabled is true. Uncomment ONE that matches your cadence:
#
# 0 * * * *    CONTENT_HOME=<CONTENT_HOME> <NODE_BIN> <ENGINE_DIR>/bin/engine.js poll-trends >> <CONTENT_HOME>/logs/trend-poll.cron.log 2>&1   # hourly (1h)
# 0 */4 * * *  CONTENT_HOME=<CONTENT_HOME> <NODE_BIN> <ENGINE_DIR>/bin/engine.js poll-trends >> <CONTENT_HOME>/logs/trend-poll.cron.log 2>&1   # every 4h
# 0 9 * * *    CONTENT_HOME=<CONTENT_HOME> <NODE_BIN> <ENGINE_DIR>/bin/engine.js poll-trends >> <CONTENT_HOME>/logs/trend-poll.cron.log 2>&1   # daily (24h) at 09:00

# OPTIONAL — the config-gated MONTHLY COMPETITOR SCAN (roadmap #5; OFF by default).
# Enable competitor_scan.enabled + competitor_scan.adapter (or "fixture" for zero-key)
# + competitor_scan.voice_calibration.enabled (if you also want proposal generation) in
# config/system.json, then schedule competitor-scan on a MONTHLY or QUARTERLY cadence.
# The --yes flag confirms the DD-18 metered-scrape gate; replace <brand-id> with your
# brand. The scan is idempotent per (brand, calendar month): a second fire in the same
# month is skipped safely. After the scan, run engine voice-calibrate --show to review
# the proposal and engine voice-calibrate --apply --consent to apply with consent.
#
# 0 7 1 * *  CONTENT_HOME=<CONTENT_HOME> <NODE_BIN> <ENGINE_DIR>/bin/engine.js competitor-scan --brand <brand-id> --yes >> <CONTENT_HOME>/logs/competitor-scan.cron.log 2>&1

# OPTIONAL — the MONTHLY BREAKOUT-DISCOVERY REMINDER (free, manual Grok; nothing to auto-run).
# Breakout discovery (new competitors + breakout keyword trends) is the FREE manual-Grok path:
# you run a prompt on your own Grok/X account and paste the result back. This line just PRINTS
# the ready-to-use prompt to a log on the 1st of each month so the manual step never slips; it
# spends nothing and writes no config. When it fires, copy the prompt into Grok, then run
# engine suggest apply --file <reply> --brand <brand-id> --yes to APPEND the confirmed items.
#
# 0 8 1 * *  CONTENT_HOME=<CONTENT_HOME> <NODE_BIN> <ENGINE_DIR>/bin/engine.js suggest prompt breakout >> <CONTENT_HOME>/logs/breakout-reminder.log 2>&1

# Notes:
#   - Logs append to $CONTENT_HOME/logs/kickoff.cron.log; the engine redacts secrets at
#     write time, but rotate/secure this file like any operational log.
#   - Drop `--now` for the scheduled morning-kickoff trigger; add it only for an
#     on-demand manual run.
#   - cron uses the system timezone; align HH:MM with your calendar's scheduler.timezone.
#   - The trend pass shares the kickoff's single-runner lock and PAUSED/budget preflight;
#     overlapping fires skip safely and a reserved trend slot filled today is not refilled.
#   - The competitor-scan pass also runs under the single-runner lock (overlapping fires
#     skip safely) and honors PAUSED + budget preflight. Voice calibration is HUMAN-ONLY:
#     the scan writes a proposal; the operator applies it with engine voice-calibrate --apply --consent.
